dataIdInfo.idAbs: The Alaska Department of Fish and Game's (ADF&G) Anadromous water bodies data is derived from the ADF&G's GIS shape files for the "Catalog of Waters Important for Spawning, Rearing or Migration of Anadromous Fishes" (referred to as the "Catalog") and the "Atlas to the Catalog of Waters Important for Spawning, Rearing or Migration of Anadromous Fishes" (referred to as the "Atlas"). It is produced for general visual reference and to aid users in generating various natural resource analyses and products. The shape files depict the known anadromous fish bearing lakes and streams within Alaska (from the mouth to the known upper extent of species usage). It incorporates data from a variety of sources including: USGS Digital Line Graph (DLG) and National Hydrography Dataset (NHD) hydrography data; Alaska Department of Natural Resources hydrography layer; and ADF&G shape files for the "Atlas" and "Catalog". ADF&G updates the Anadromous Streams data regularly. Note that stream numbers, locations, extent of cataloged habitat or species utilization of a given stream may change from year to year. Data for the shape files are current as of the 2014 revision of the "Atlas to the Catalog of Waters Important for the Spawning, Rearing or Migration of Anadromous Fishes" and the "Catalog of Waters Important for the Spawning, Rearing or Migration of Anadromous Fishes" effective June 1, 2014. This particular data layer is for the Southeastern Region of Alaska.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: Anadromous Waters Catalog data are used to specify the water bodies referred to in AS 16.05.871 for the protection of waters important for the spawning, rearing or migration of anadromous fishes.

LegConsts.othConsts: Users must assume responsibility to determine the usability of this data for their purposes. These data are public information and provided for general visual reference and to aid users in generating various natural resource analyses and products. As such they have no access constraints other than registration with the ADF&G Division of Sport Fish through the division's Anadromous Waters Catalog download site (see Distribution Information Section). This registration information is used to ensure distribution of the most current public information and will be used to mail notifications of data changes. If you have obtained this coverage through the ADF&G site please refer requests for copies of the data to the ADF&G download site or to the ADF&G, Division of Sport Fish (see Distribution Information Section). If you have obtained this data through another source please contact the ADF&G through the download site or email to register and ensure you have the most up to date data.

Stream mouth point and upper reach point with interconnecting hydrography arc data are complete for the streams listed in the AWC Hydrography and species utilization data is completed for water bodies within the Southeastern Region. To be included in the Catalog of Waters Important for the Spawning, Rearing or Migration of Anadromous Fishes (and its associated Atlas), water bodies must be documented as supporting some life function of an anadromous fish species (salmon, trout, char, whitefish, sturgeon, etc.) Anadromous fish must have been seen or collected and identified by a qualified observer. The Catalog and Atlas currently contain 18,248 streams, rivers, lakes or polygons around the state which have been specified as being important for the spawning, rearing or migration of anadromous fish. Based upon thorough surveys of a few drainages it is believed that this number represents less than 50% of the streams, rivers and lakes actually used by anadromous species. It is estimated that at least an additional 20,000 or more anadromous water bodies have not been identified or specified under AS 16.05.871.

The attribute accuracy is tested visually by comparing the source with hard copy printouts or interactive displays of anadromous streams on a computer. Also programs are run to check species data accuracy by water body and by watershed.

Historically point data were digitized from 1:63,360 USGS maps where available and 1:250,000 in other areas. Presently stream points are snapped to endpoints of hydrography derived from NHD (National Hydrography Dataset) and where NHD hydrography is not available from USGS DLGs (Digital Line Graphics), hydrography datasets from USFS, ADNR and from data digitized from maps, imagery, georectified aerial photos, or taken from GPS locations. Modifications were based on detailed aerial photography, imagery, georectified aerial photos, and information collected from regional experts. Verification of data consists of paper plots or digital pdf graphic files of maps checked against USGS mylar base maps and original submissions. No accuracy assessment has been performed against real world positions.

prcStep.stepDesc: Historically upper and lower points depicting the extent of anadromous streams and species points were digitized from 1:63,360 scale USGS maps or 1:250,000 scale USGS maps where 1:63,360 maps did not exist. Older points, approximately pre-1988 may have been digitized from paper versions of these maps. Thus the latitude, longitude and legal descriptions of these latter points may have strayed from their actual locations due to shrinkage of the paper maps prior to digitizing. After 1988, digitizing was done on mylar base maps. At that time the mouth and upper reach points were connected by a straight line. Latitude, longitude and legal descriptions were calculated from a Fortran-based program outside of the GIS environment that derived the locations from BLM AIH files. As digital hydrography became available these straight lines were replaced with hydrography from the best available datasets including those from NHD, USGS, USFS and ADNR. Where no digital source was available for hydrography, arcs were digitized from georectified aerial photos, orthophotos, digital raster graphics (DRG), imagery, or from gps points obtained in the field by biologists. Currently upper reach and mouth points are snapped to the endpoints of these added hydrography arcs. During the process of replacing straight lines, many upper and lower points have been moved to correspond to the updated hydrography arcs. These areas have also undergone additional checks for accuracy.
